89. ADP Security: How to Protect Your Password and Account Information 

As an employee with payroll managed by ADP, it is important to ensure your password and account information are protected. ADP is committed to safeguarding your personal and financial data, and this article will provide tips and best practices to help you keep your account secure.

1. Create a Strong Password

The first step to protecting your account information is to create a strong password. A strong password should consist of at least 8 characters and include a combination of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and special characters. Avoid using easily guessable information like your name, date of birth, or phone number.

2. Use Two-Factor Authentication

ADP offers two-factor authentication, which adds an extra layer of security to your account. This feature requires a second form of verification, usually a code sent to your phone, in addition to your password. Enabling this feature can help prevent unauthorized access to your account, even if someone has your password.

3. Keep Your Account Information Up-to-Date

Make sure your account information is accurate and up-to-date. This includes your email address and phone number. If any of your personal information changes, update your account immediately.

4. Avoid Phishing Scams

Phishing is a common tactic used by scammers to obtain sensitive information. These scams can come in the form of emails, texts, or phone calls. Always be cautious when clicking on links or downloading attachments, and be wary of any messages that ask for your ADP login credentials.

5. Log Out When Finished

When you are finished using your ADP account, make sure to log out completely. This is especially important if you are using a shared computer or device.

By following these tips and best practices, you can help protect your ADP account and ensure your personal and financial information remains secure. If you have any questions or concerns, please contact ADP customer support for assistance.